1. Project Topic¶

This is the report of Supervised Learning for the past Kaggle competition IEEE-CIS Fraud Detection. The purpose of this project is to predict fraud from transactions with good accuracy (auc 0.9 in kaggle private score). I selected this project because there are some problems in data which need to be treated properly:

Problems in the Data

  • data imbalance: only 3.5% of label is positive in train data.
  • Too many features: the data has about 400 of columns
  • anonymized features: columns do not have specific name.
  • missing values
  • correlation between features

Since the data consists of both categorical and numerical features, tree-based methods are appropriate. Therefore, RandomForestClassifier and XG Boost are selected.

Data Source

https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/ieee-fraud-detection/data

#function to plot histogram of train and test data
#y axis represent ratio of value 
def ratio_x(df1, df2, select):
    Y = "TransactionID"

    n_df1 = df1.shape[0]
    df1_2 = df1[[select, Y]].groupby(select).count().rename({Y:"count"}, axis =1).sort_values("count", ascending = False).reset_index()
    df1_2["ratio"] = (df1_2["count"]/n_df1)
    
    n_df2 = df2.shape[0]
    df2_2 = df2[[select, Y]].groupby(select).count().rename({Y:"count"}, axis =1).sort_values("count", ascending = False).reset_index()
    df2_2["ratio"] = (df2_2["count"]/n_df1)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (14, 3))
    sns.barplot(data = df1_2.head(10), y = "ratio", x = select, ax = ax[0])
    sns.barplot(data = df2_2.head(10), y = "ratio", x = select, ax = ax[1])
    ax[0].set_title(select + ": ratio of top10 values (train data)")
    ax[1].set_title(select + ": ratio of top10 values (test data)")
    for i in range(2):
        ax[i].set_ylim(0, 1)

3.3 Imputation¶

How to impute NaN depends on type of data, ratio of NaN, and data distribution. If data is numeric, mean value is selected. If data is categorical, and NaN ratio is small and the one value occupies high ratio, mode (most frequent value) is selected. Otherwize, new category (Z or -255) fills NaN of categorical columns.

Mean Value

  • dist1
  • Numeric Group C, D, V

Most Frequent Value

  • card3, card4, card5
  • add2

"Z"

  • card4, card6
  • P_emaildomain, R_emaildomain
  • M1, M2, M3, M7, M9
  • M4, M5, M6, M8

-255

  • card2
  • addr1
In [33]:
def impute_num(df, label, num):
    filter1 = df[label].isna()
    df.loc[filter1,label] = num

3.4 Removing Outliers¶

Negative value in numeric C, D and V should be mistake or bug. It exists only in few rows of D4, D11, and D15. Those value should be removed (replaced by mode).

In [37]:
## Outliers
labels = ["D4", "D11", "D15"]
for label in labels:
    filter1 = train_tr[label] < 0
    train_tr.loc[filter1,label] = train_tr[label].mode()[0]

4. EDA and Feature Engineering¶

4.1 Time Series Feature¶

In the data, there is a column TransactionDT which has integer values. The name means transaction date and time that can be converted into hour, day, month, and year. Then, interesting trends are visible. Fraud is highest probability at hour (HourD) 7. HourCount (#transaction/hour) has 24 hours cycle. DayCount (#transaction/day) has 7 days cycle.

In [39]:
# Function to generate new features

def TS_Features(df):
    
    df['Day']  = df['TransactionDT']//(3600*24)
    df['Hour']  = df['TransactionDT'] // 3600
    df['Month']  = df['TransactionDT'] // (3600*24*30)
    df['Year']  = df['TransactionDT'] // (3600*24*365)
    #hour of the day
    df['HourD']  = (df['TransactionDT'] // 3600 ) % 24
    #day of the year
    df['DayY']  = df['TransactionDT']//(3600*24) % 365
    df['WeekM']  = df['TransactionDT']//(3600*24*7) % 4
    
                
    #number of transaction by day and hour
    DayCount = df[["Day",ID]].groupby("Day").count().rename({ID:"DayCount"}, axis = 1).reset_index()
    HourCount= df[["Hour",ID]].groupby("Hour").count().rename({ID:"HourCount"}, axis = 1).reset_index()
    
    #merge feature columns
    df2 = df[["Day", ID]].merge(DayCount, on = "Day", how ="left").copy()
    df["DayCount"] = df2["DayCount"]
    df2 = df[["Hour", ID]].merge(HourCount, on = "Hour", how ="left").copy()
    df["HourCount"] = df2["HourCount"]

4.4 Encoding Categorical Variables¶

To make ML efficient, categorical variables are encoded into probability of fraud.

In [55]:
def value_rank_df(select, min_count = 200):
    
    Y = "isFraud"
    
    df = train_tr[[select, Y]].groupby(select).mean()
    filter1 = (train_tr[[select, Y]].groupby(select).count() > min_count)[Y]
    df2 = df.loc[filter1,:]
    
    keys = list(df2.index)
    vals = df2[Y].to_numpy()
    
    dic1 = {}
    for i in range(len(vals)):
        dic1[keys[i]] = vals[i]
    
    return dic1#, df2.sort_values(Y, ascending = False)
In [56]:
def find_P(dic1, val):
    
    try:
        p = dic1[val]
        return p
    except KeyError:
        return 0.03499 #average probability

5. ML¶

5.1 Splitting Data¶

For time series data, train and validation should not be shuffled. Thus, in the split_train_val function, train should be the first 70% and validation is latter 30%. Since the label Y (isFraud) is highly imbalanced (96.5% is negative), the function includes sampling of negative cases.

In [64]:
def split_train_val(X, y, train_pct):
    
    n = X.shape[0]
    n_train = int(n*train_pct)
    
    #validation is latter 
    X_val = X.iloc[n_train:,:]
    y_val = y[n_train:]
    
    # positive index
    filter1 = y[0:n_train] == 1
    n_pos = np.sum(filter1)
    pos_sample = np.where(filter1)[0]
    
    # negative index
    neg_indx = np.where(y[0:n_train] == 0)[0]
    np.random.seed(1)
    
    # sample negative same quantity as positive
    neg_sample = np.random.choice(neg_indx, n_pos)
    
    sample_index = np.concatenate((pos_sample, neg_sample))
    
    X_train = X.iloc[sample_index,:]
    y_train =  y[sample_index]
    
    return X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val

5.1 Random Forest Classifier¶

To prevent overfitting of RandomForestClassifier, important features selected first. Then, max depth and ccp-alpha are tuned.

5.1.1 Feature Selection¶

In [70]:
def train_and_validate(clf, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val):
    
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    yhat_train = clf.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]
    yhat_val = clf.predict_proba(X_val)[:,1]
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_train, yhat_train, pos_label=1)
    train_auc = metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_val, yhat_val, pos_label=1)
    val_auc = metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)
    
    return train_auc, val_auc

6. Conclusion and Discussion¶

Scores: RandomForest achieved the objective (auc 0.9)

As a result, RandomForstClassifier achieved the purpose (auc 0.9) of this project. The model seems to be appropriate because test auc is almost same as the validation auc. On the otherhand, XGBoost had only 0.886 in test auc, although validatin auc (0.9137) was higher than randomforest (0.9043). RandomForestClassifier did not need countermeasures against overfitting.

What improved val auc of RF is reduction of features and max depth tuning. It is possible that reduction of features prevents useless trees in RF.

RandomForest XGBoost
Train AUC 0.999 0.999
Val AUC 0.914 0.921
Test AUC (kaggle private score) 0.901 0.883
Max Depth 25 12
N tree 300 (500 for test) 100
N feature 150 231(all)

Why XG Boost score dropped in test data?

XGBoost must be better than RF at getting higher auc if test data distribution is similar to train data. That's why val score was much better than RF. According to TransactionDT column, test data is newer (later) in date. Therefore, there is no guarantee that transactions maintain similar patterns.

How to improve auc?

First, it is necessary to find meaning of new values in categorical columns. There are some new values in test data which did not apper in train data. For example, card1 of test data has more than 3000 values which are not in train data. Since, card1 is ranked in the top 5 of feature importance, new values must be the cause of worse auc in test data.

Second, the prediction must be corrected according to the difference of data distribution. RandomForest and XGB assumed that train and test distributions are the same. Parhaps some features must contain regression methods.

Third, more effective features must be created. It is possible if I could find clear patterns of fraudulent transactions. Hence, deeper analysis in EDA is important.

Other takeaways

According to feature importance of RF and XGB, I got following insights:

  • Time Series Features works well in tree-based method: RF and XGB do not work like ARIMA model, but feature engineering compensated this short coming. e.g. DayY (day of the year) ranked high in importance.
  • NaN has meaning: SumNaN ranked in the top 10.
  • Probability encoding is efficient but has risk in validation: some categorical variable has too many unique values such as card1. Encoding value into probability reduces number of split of tree in such cases. As shown in following examples, there are specific cards which often used for fraudulent transactions.
